y, the government said.   The Labor Department said Wednesday that productivity in thenon-farm portion of the economy increased at an annual rate of 0.7percent in the April-June period.   That was up from the 0.2 percent gain reported in preliminarydata last month and much better than the 1.3 percent decline in thefirst quarter.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Now that Congress has passed the savings andloan rescue, it should consider changes in deposit insurance,including a reduction in the $100,000 coverage limit, the chairmanof the House Banking Committee says.   ``I believe it wouldn't hurt any to reduce it a few thousanddollars. I think it'll make the stockholders and the depositors alittle bit more careful about what they're doing with theirinstitution,'' Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, said Wednesday.   The Sandamp;L bill, signed into law Aug. 9 by President Bush, directsthe Treasury Department to finish a study of the deposit insuranceissue in 18 months.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The fate of hundreds of savings institutionshangs on the interpretation of confusing capital standards adoptedby Congress last month, regulators said.   The key reform in the bill requires Sandamp;L owners to risk more oftheir own capital as a buffer between losses and government depositinsurance funds.   However, Sandamp;L regulators said Wednesday they are not sure exactlyhow tough the standard should be. The problem is the final bill wascobbled together from very different versions passed separately bythe House and Senate, they said.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Car and truck sales in the United States soared21.4 percent in late August over last year as customers tookadvantage of end-of-the-model-year sales and looming price increases.   For the entire month, with import sales included, car and trucksales rose 8.4 percent compared with August of last year, automakerssaid Wednesday. Domestic vehicles showed a significant gain.   Vehicles made by the eight automakers with U.S. plants sold at anaverage rate of 49,276 a day during the Aug. 21-31 period this year,compared with a daily rate of 40,578 during the same time last year.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   While Miss America contestants stroll down the runway in AtlanticCity, N.J., next week, another string of beauties will chug into NewYork Harbor for the first-ever Tugboat Beauty Contest, complete withBert Parks as emcee.   The contestants in the Sept. 13 event will be strutting morehorsepower than cheesecake, but organizers believe beauty _ when itcomes to tugboats _ is definitely in the eye of the beholder.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co., a relatively small player in theworld of big trucks, is negotiating with Saab-Scania AB of Stockholmwith an eye on the Swedish company's truck business, experts say.   Because it has been making and selling cars in Europe for morethan 60 years, Ford wouldn't need Saab's car distribution network.Ford, in fact, sells more cars in Sweden than does Saab.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market Wednesday suffered the first sizable drop sincereaching all-time highs last month in an atmosphere of uncertaintyabout the outlook for Federal Reserve policy and interest rates. Butthe Dow Jones average of 30 industrials remained within strikingdistance of record levels.   A healthy bond market helped arrest the slide in stocks, whichsaw the Dow Jones average fall nearly 40 points around midday. Atthe close the average was down 24.89 points at 2,719.79.   The dollar retreated after its recent surge, while gold pricesrose.   Copper futures prices tumbled; oil futures rose; meat futuresrallied; and corn futures gained.</TEXT></DOC>